column168: ABOUT 1:10 P.M., FEBRUARY 18, 1984, NORTH LEAD SWITCH CREW WAS SWITCHING HE AD END OF TRAIN FM-18 AT TEXARKANA YARD WHEN THEY DETECTED CHEMICAL ODOR IN THE AIR AND, UPON INVESTIGATION, DISCOVERED THAT SIXTH CAR FROM ENGINE, ET CX 651, LOADED TANK CAR OF BUTYRALDEHYDE LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET.  SWITC H ENGINE CREW, A CARMAN AND A CLERK WORKING IN THE AREA WERE TAKEN TO ST. M ICHEAL'S HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION ACCOUNT INHALATION OF FUMES FROM THIS CAR .  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED.  TEXAS EASTMAN AND CHEMTREC NOTIFIED AT 3:00 P.M..  LEAK WAS TEMPORARILY STOPED AT 6:40 P.M. BY MISSOURI PACIFIC ME CHANICAL FOREMAN P. C. SCHILLING, WHO APPLIED GASKET TO BOTTOM OUTLET PLATE AND REPLACED MISSING NUT AND BOLT.  TEXAS EASTMAN REPRESENTATIVE LEE RADCL IFF ARRIVED AT 9:00 P.M., CHECKED TOP LOADING VALVE ON CAR AND FOUND THAT I T WAS NOT PROPERLY SEATED, CAUSING BOTTOM OUTLET TO DROP DOWN, ALLOWING CHE MICAL TO LEAK FROM BOTTOM OUTLET.  MR. RADCLIFF OPENED TOP VALVE AND RESEAT ED IT, COMPLETELY STOPPING ANY LEAKAGE, MAKING CAR SAFE FOR MOVEMENT.  CAR MOVED OUT OF TEXARKANA TO TEXAS EASTMAN AT LONGVIEW ON TRAIN LH-18, ARRIVIN G LONGVIEW AT 6:30 A.M., FEBRUARY 19, 1984.
